roteins, ignoring things like imprinting and X-inactivation, which is a bit more advanced to grasp."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8a1c3093e5ea650e39c4a875f62a0bd4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4971,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4971/tmottm","reputation":320,"display_name":"TMOTTM","accept_rate":25},"score":0,"post_id":40316,"edited":false,"creation_date":1448311935,"comment_id":69206,"body":"I dont find it a dummy question. Article &quot;gene expression&quot; on wikipedia does not provide a solution to this question."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b806b8bb7c6fa8e70f2c0634d1b6707e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19868,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19868/mtp","reputation":71,"display_name":"mtp"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e6302a08505d86d2a5a7cc12ade9e44e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18883,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18883/arcadium","reputation":90,"display_name":"Arcadium","accept_rate":100},"score":2,"post_id":40334,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446816580,"comment_id":67829,"body":"According to some moderators you need to go into the intricacies of monoallelic expression in detail or else this is an incomplete answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b806b8bb7c6fa8e70f2c0634d1b6707e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19868,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19868/mtp","reputation":71,"display_name":"mtp"},"score":0,"post_id":40334,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e6302a08505d86d2a5a7cc12ade9e44e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":18883,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/18883/arcadium","reputation":90,"display_name":"Arcadium","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446822170,"comment_id":67845,"body":"@OmarMourad how is it now? thanks for the feedback, this is the first question I&#39;ve answered on SE"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446822585,"creation_date":1446813041,"body":"<p>The majority of normal autosomal genes have biallelic expression, i.e. the alleles on both chromosomes are used to make protein. This is why mutations in a gene which cause non-function of the product can be silent if the mutation is heterozygous (only found on one of the alleles), because the effect is masked by the second, fully-functional, copy of the gene. In other cases heterozygous mutations may cause slight phenotypes, because half of the protein produced is non-functional.<\/p>\n\n<p>A small minority of autosomal genes have monoallelic expression, through a process called imprinting. This is where one of the alleles of the gene is modified by methylation of the DNA, or of histones (the proteins which are used to package and condense DNA). This imprinting switches off the expression of that allele, so that protein is only made from the other allele of the gene. Usually in this case, which allele is switched off depends on which parent it came from.<\/p>\n\n<p>Things are slightly more complicated in the case of genes on X or Y chromosomes. Men have only a single X chromosome, and a single Y chromosome. This means that any mutation on X or Y which causes a phenotype will always present itself, because there is no second copy to mask it.<\/p>\n\n<p>In the case of women, who have two X chromosomes and no Y, something similar to imprinting happens, where one of the X chromosomes is chosen to be inactivated. This X-inactivation process occurs very early in development, and the inactive X chromosome is kept that way for the rest of that person's life. In this case, however, the choice of which chromosome is inactivated is not dependent on which parent the chromosome came from, and is entirely random.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Some further reading:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/monoallelic-expression-8813275\">http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/monoallelic-expression-8813275<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/genetic-imprinting-and-x-inactivation-1066\">http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/genetic-imprinting-and-x-inactivation-1066<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":40334,"question_id":40316,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1446822585}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40316/which-of-the-two-chromosomes-in-a-pair-is-expressed","last_activity_date":1446822585,"creation_date":1446758355,"answer_count":1,"title":"Which of the two chromosomes in a pair is expressed?","body":"<p>I have completely dummy question.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have 23 pairs of chromosomes in the cells 23 single coming from my mother and 23 single from my father. So how my cell choose which chromosome, mother's or father's to use to synthesize peptides?<\/p>\n","question_id":40316,"tags":["genetics","chromosome"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":40334,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":154,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1446772641},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9d846fecc171a713e733b748fc00d94b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19870,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19870/kiuzio2","reputation":11,"display_name":"kiuzio2"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XdJ9g.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19432,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19432/akadrhouse","reputation":448,"display_name":"akaDrHouse"},"score":0,"post_id":40339,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446820333,"comment_id":67838,"body":"The way this is worded is confusing. The exhaled air you are referring to is from a maximal inspiration to a maximal expiration, also known as FVC or forced vital capacity.  FVC + another 1/2 liter is a good good approximation of total lung volume."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":0,"post_id":40339,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/XdJ9g.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19432,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19432/akadrhouse","reputation":448,"display_name":"akaDrHouse"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446820979,"comment_id":67842,"body":"Is is, but I figured I&#39;d gloss over most of it given the precision implicit in the question. If the speed of expiration isn&#39;t being measured &quot;how much time you blow&quot; won&#39;t give you an accurate representation of FVC at all. And the total lung volume is only first-order related to the VO2max, which you could meaningfully compare to athletes."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446819946,"creation_date":1446819946,"body":"<p>There is. <\/p>\n\n<p>At a first approximation the total lung capacity is the anatomical dead space(the volume of your trachea, more or less) + the tidal volume(the volume of each breath). It's slightly more complicated than that based on the differences in how deep you breathe and how often you can breathe, but at a first approximation exhaled air + half a liter(plusminus) = lung capacity.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40339,"question_id":40336,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0la1I.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":483