 segment will be determined. <\/p>\n\n<p>Can anyone confirm?<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qEi7O.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/qEi7O.png\" alt=\"the image from my textbook\"><\/a><\/p>\n","question_id":40266,"tags":["development"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":19,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1446618031},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2e2c1227e8568057070f57cf5f66b87f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":6660,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6660/saalem","reputation":46,"display_name":"Saalem"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/QarBg.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1368,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1368/daniel","reputation":1849,"display_name":"daniel","accept_rate":68},"score":12,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1399573201,"creation_date":1399573201,"body":"<p>First, \"premature ejaculation\" is a matter of definition. Here is an authoritative source. From the American Urological Association's news site, a 2008 notice:<\/p>\n\n<p>'The ISSM [Int'l Soc. for Sexual Med.] has defined premature ejaculation as \u201ca male sexual dysfunction characterized by ejaculation which always or nearly always occurs prior to or within about one minute of vaginal penetration; and, inability to delay ejaculation on all or nearly all vaginal penetrations; and, negative personal consequences, such as distress, bother, frustration and/or the avoidance of sexual intimacy.\u201d'<\/p>\n\n<p>The main author of the ISSM paper was Sharlip. Sharlip ID, Hellstrom WJG, Broderick GA: The ISSM definition of premature ejaculation: a contemporary, evidence-based definition. J Urol, suppl., 2008; 179: 340, abstract 988.<\/p>\n\n<p>If this is the threshold for PE then it is not a stretch to say that almost anything else is within normal limits. If \"typical latency is 4-8 minutes\" then 1.5 minutes would be near the low extreme of normal. <\/p>\n\n<p>I think the issue of stress is at least as important as duration. If something isn't bothersome it never becomes a medical issue.<\/p>\n\n<p>A nice study involving 491 men is reviewed <a href=\"http://www.medicine.ox.ac.uk/bandolier/band137/b137-4.html\">here<\/a>. The mean IELT (intravaginal ejaculatory latency time) is 5.4 minutes. As you can see from the graph on the site, most of the results are contained in the first few minutes with a tail of longer times to the right. <\/p>\n\n<p>The original source for that information is MC Waldinger et al. A multinational population survey on intravaginal ejaculation latency time. Journal of Sexual Medicine 2005 2: 492-497. This also addresses your question about the timing of measurement--it's post-entry. <\/p>\n\n<p>An expert in this area could update my information but it's a recent average so I don't think things have changed much.<\/p>\n","answer_id":17260,"question_id":17253,"up_vote_count":12}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/17253/what-is-the-normal-duration-of-human-sexual-intercourse","last_activity_date":1446611834,"creation_date":1399562839,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the normal duration of human sexual intercourse?","body":"<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premature_ejaculation\">Wikipedia<\/a> is saying:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Men's typical ejaculatory latency is approximately 4\u20138 minutes<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>How the researchers measured this? How did they know if the test subjects weren't suffering from premature ejaculation?<\/p>\n\n<p>And is this measured from the start of erection or from the start of penetration?<\/p>\n","question_id":17253,"tags":["human-biology","physiology"],"score":9,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1446613925,"is_answered":true,"view_count":24841,"up_vote_count":9,"last_edit_date":1402210007},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10105431372802249/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":17143,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17143/christopher-hendrickson","reputation":1,"display_name":"Christopher Hendrickson"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":36655,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438814039,"comment_id":61142,"body":"I can&#39;t think of any predictive tools, but I think you should simplify the system as much as possible first. Instead of trying to express the ncRNA in plant, get the purified plant protein and purified ncRNA, maybe by in vitro transcription. Mix the two together and see if you can use coprecipitation or crosslinking or something to look for binding. Fluorescent anisotropy might be cool if you have a fluoremeter with polarizers, you could label the RNA with a flourophore, then measure the tumbling rate, once it binds the protein the tumbling should slow down. Use the human protein as control."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8338f9b96b1c61599df745d61145b0c2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15878,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15878/243","reputation":959,"display_name":"243"},"score":-1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10105431372802249/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":17143,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17143/christopher-hendrickson","reputation":1,"display_name":"Christopher Hendrickson"},"score":0,"post_id":36661,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438829970,"comment_id":61155,"body":"With my experimental plan, I plan to use a reporter transcript.  I will be able to say more than &quot;it&#39;s an RNA binding protein&quot;.  My primary concern is precisely that the &quot;plant protein may not recognize the same RNA sequence to the human protein&quot; if at all.  SELEX and CHIP will likely help me in my objective here.  Thank you for your suggestions."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":36661,"edited":false,"creation_date":1438865934,"comment_id":61175,"body":"I would be careful using SELEX to find endogenous RNAs that bind the protein, it would probably find an RNA aptamer that binds the protein well, but there is no guarantee that the resulting RNA would actually bind in a relevant manner, or just be a novel sequence that happens to bind well. Being able to make an RNA to bind almost anything is why SELEX is so useful."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1438824978,"creation_date":1438824978,"body":"<p>The ncRNA sequence from human may bind to the plant protein in the plant cells, but so what? You may be able to say the plant protein works as RNA binding protein, but no more than that.\nAnother concern is that the plant protein may not recognize the same RNA sequence to the human protein.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are several ways to find RNA partners of RNA binding proteins.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://cshprotocols.cshlp.org/content/2013/2/pdb.prot072934.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">SELEX<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This method is used to find consensus sequences that your protein recognizes in vitro. Once you find consensus sequences, you can search ncRNAs from the plant.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CLIP\" rel=\"nofollow\">CLIP<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This is similar to Chip assay. You could find real targets of your RNA binding proteins<\/p>\n","answer_id":36661,"question_id":36655,"up_vote_count":0