">MD simulation<\/a> carried out to investigate the biophysicochemistry of spontaneous bilayer assembly. There, lipids start in random orientations. The ordered bilayers we know and love spontaneously assemble in under 100ns. <\/p>\n\n<p>It would appear that the conditions for an ordered bilayer are so favourable that they take precedence over any other orientation or combination.<\/p>\n\n<h1>Why use membranes?<\/h1>\n\n<p>Compartmentalising the cell has lots of advantages and purposes. Broadly this is to create different sets of conditions (chemical and biological) inside the cells. This allows more efficient functioning and advanced catabolic and metabolic processing.<\/p>\n","answer_id":36799,"question_id":9261,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1375440688/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":4139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4139/johntreml","reputation":536,"display_name":"johntreml"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"score":0,"post_id":36802,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446617737,"comment_id":67656,"body":"You&#39;ve given some reasons why membranes are useful, but nothing about why a <b>bi<\/b>layer is important."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1375440688/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":4139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4139/johntreml","reputation":536,"display_name":"johntreml"},"score":0,"post_id":36802,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f437d9a11deebd214089822c26197f35?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3553,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3553/james","reputation":4533,"display_name":"James","accept_rate":83},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446646428,"comment_id":67678,"body":"You&#39;re right, Good Gravy. I think I had read through that part of the question entirely. I think I would say that sometimes things just work out. Phospholipids are used not just in cell membranes, but also with fat-transport molecules, etc. Certainly this use in particular is millions of years downstream from the &#39;decision&#39; to use phospholipids to generate cell membranes, but it does illustrate how an amphipathic molecule might be more useful than one that is not. Moreover, once half the membrane molecule developed, the solution self-assembled, negating the need for further &#39;development&#39;."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1439424232,"creation_date":1439424232,"body":"<p>Membranes provide a number of benefits to organisms:\n1. They represent the bounds of organism...\nIf not for the membrane, how would you establish the (physical) limits of the organism? Would the organism be just naked DNA (I'm using this as shorthand for (genetic material')? If it made proteins from this DNA, would they be part of the organism or just environmental elements that may act on the DNA.<\/p>\n\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li><p>They act as sites of metabolism...\nThere are a number of viruses that lack membranes, but these 'organisms' are not universally considered alive. One of the best arguments against viruses being alive is that they do not carry out metabolism (producing energy / breaking things down / building things up). Many metabolic reactions cells participate in occur within and across membranes.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>They conveniently self-assemble from composite parts and can react and respond to the environment without 'breaking'.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>They allow organisms to concentrate things. Imagine you find yourself in a rich environment and produce sugars for use later. Where can you store them? Cells also store ions like Ca++ which can be released rapidly to have an effect on the organism. <\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n","answer_id":36802,"question_id":9261,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/9261/why-do-cell-membranes-have-a-lipid-bilayer","last_activity_date":1446572873,"creation_date":1373733874,"answer_count":5,"title":"Why do cell membranes have a lipid bilayer?","body":"<p>Many cells have a cell membrane composed of two layers of lipids, why is it two layers and not just one? <\/p>\n\n<p>What purpose do the membranes serve?<\/p>\n","question_id":9261,"tags":["cell-biology","microbiology"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":9264,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":6601,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1373788361},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1LBbl.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19754/jean-paul","reputation":91,"display_name":"Jean-Paul","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/635f7658ac7395f2e294baf3dfc55e96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19538,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19538/k-gargiullo","reputation":59,"display_name":"K Gargiullo"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1LBbl.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19754/jean-paul","reputation":91,"display_name":"Jean-Paul","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":40247,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446577005,"comment_id":67599,"body":"Thank you for your answer. I understand that the brain processes information in different clusters but I can&#39;t grasp the theory that conscious thoughts are distributed over clusters of neurons. Taking the Excel spreadsheet example: even though we don&#39;t see the lower-level tasks, we are <i>still<\/i> presented with the lower-level&#39;s output. This is what my question is about: assuming that A and B are such lower-level processing clusters, they must report to some central place in order for the information to enter our conscious thought. Much like when I use an Excel formula, I am given the result."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1LBbl.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19754/jean-paul","reputation":91,"display_name":"Jean-Paul","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":40247,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446577266,"comment_id":67602,"body":"It makes sense to me that such clusters can intercommunicate, but one of the clusters has to report back to some centralised &#39;conscious thought&#39;. How else can I think of an abstract principle? Surely, when thinking of this principle a cluster of neurons fires. But is this firing all there is? Is my conscious thought within this cluster of firing neurons or does the cluster communicate to a centralised area (like the hippocampus), where connections to my short- and long-term memory are also present (this seems more likely to me than to say that conscious thought is the firing of neurons alone)?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/635f7658ac7395f2e294baf3dfc55e96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19538,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19538/k-gargiullo","reputation":59,"display_name":"K Gargiullo"},"score":0,"post_id":40247,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1LBbl.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19754/jean-paul","reputation":91,"display_name":"Jean-Paul","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446580660,"comment_id":67609,"body":"@Jean-Paul Thanks for the clarification on the question! Unfortunately I&#39;m not sure there&#39;s a real satisfactory answer out there, but let me try...  First, it might help if you try to think of higher-level brain activity less like a modular machine and more like an overall  pattern of firing. We talk about areas of the brain being involved in one thing and it&#39;s easy to get caught up in that, especially when you&#39;re looking at imagine studies where it looks like one area lights up neat and tidy."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/635f7658ac7395f2e294baf3dfc55e96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19538,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19538/k-gargiullo","reputation":59,"display_name":"K Gargiullo"},"score":1,"post_id":40247,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1LBbl.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19754/jean-paul","reputation":91,"display_name":"Jean-Paul","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446580679,"comment_id":67610,"body":"The truth is that most of your brain is active most of the time. In order to get that clean picture that you see in the paper, they had to do a lot of statistics and filter out a lot of noise and hope that their baseline was decent. This is a big issue in functional brain imaging, especially fMRI, and it&#39;s pretty interesting so I&#39;m going to paste some references at the bottom in case you want to check it out. That&#39;s not to say that localization isn&#39;t useful! But it has to be taken as one data point, not the whole picture."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/635f7658ac7395f2e294baf3dfc55e96?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19538,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19538/k-gargiullo","reputation":59,"display_name":"K Gargiullo"},"score":1,"post_id":40247,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1LBbl.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19754,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19754/jean-paul","reputation":91,"display_na