olarizing OFF-bipolars. Some ON-center neurons also seem to respond to the removal of the deformation. Bipolar cells connect to the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retinal_ganglion_cell\" rel=\"nofollow\">retinal ganglion cells<\/a>. These ganglion cells carry visual information from the retina via their axons in the <a href=\"http://www.healthline.com/human-body-maps/optic-nerve\" rel=\"nofollow\">optic nerve<\/a> to the brain. Hence, to answer your question: yes, pressure phosphenes are related to activity in the optic nerve.<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0042698989901235\" rel=\"nofollow\">Grüsser <em>et al<\/em>., <em>Vis Res<\/em> (1989); <strong>29<\/strong>(2): 181\u201394<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":40225,"question_id":40142,"up_vote_count":6,"last_edit_date":1446523357}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40142/what-causes-the-bright-flash-of-light-when-poking-my-eye","last_activity_date":1446523556,"creation_date":1446329998,"answer_count":1,"title":"What causes the bright flash of light when poking my eye?","body":"<p>Recently, I poked myself in between my eye and eye socket, right below my eyebrow, and sometimes I would get this flash of light. Others have tried this too, and they also had a flash of light. I am wondering why is this the case. Does it have to do with the nerves in the eye? <\/p>\n","question_id":40142,"tags":["vision","neurophysiology","human-eye"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":40225,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_count":145,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1446523556},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/392829bf28778fcbb8ae53033c98df8c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16192,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16192/zenadix","reputation":126,"display_name":"Zenadix"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avat