 to combat dessication. But when it rains, they \"come out,\" just like many amphibians.<\/p>\n\n<p>I should qualify the first sentence to say SOME snails. There are aquatic snails and terrestrial snails (which I'm sure you're referring to). Aquatic snails generally have gills, while most terrestrial snails have a single lung (I think).<\/p>\n\n<p>Slugs, like snails, are generally found in moist areas and can often be seen after a rain.<\/p>\n\n<p>I don't know of a single reference that pulls it all together, but this is a good place to start...<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.molluscs.at/gastropoda/index.html?/gastropoda/morphology/respiration.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">The Living World of Molluscs<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":40182,"question_id":40179,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1446437927},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1df509e5691192420165314163ecee4b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19801,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19801/user19801","reputation":11,"display_name":"user19801"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef69e4c7ba6adf44fc3d17c4bbacec01?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":10401,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10401/tanmath","reputation":1620,"display_name":"TanMath","accept_rate":58},"score":0,"post_id":40218,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446507308,"comment_id":67529,"body":"Welcome to Biology.SE! Can you please add references? (I am not trying to be rude) I like your answer, but references would certainly complete it."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446503276,"creation_date":1446503276,"body":"<p>In most species, slugs and snails survive droughts (which would otherwise kill them by dehydration) by creating \"slime tombs\" (initially-viscous bubbles of slime) around themselves. these tombs or pellets will quickly dry out, on the surface, while resisting total dehydration. When it rains, these capsules will re-hydrate or \"melt,\" beginning on the surface, and the creatures will crawl free. \nBecause they've gone without food, they're ravenous, and go everywhere, \"rasping\" softened nutrients from the surfaces of plants and even objects where \"blossoming\" single-cell organisms (also recently re-hydrated) can be found. <\/p>\n","answer_id":40218,"question_id":40179,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40179/why-do-snails-come-out-after-the-rain","last_activity_date":1446503276,"creation_date":1446423067,"answer_count":2,"title":"Why do snails come out after the rain?","body":"<p>Many times, when there is rain after a <em>long time<\/em>, snails come out afterwards, and you can see snails and slugs everywhere! I have two questions:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Why do they come out after the rain?<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Where are they usually found, not after a rain?<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Note that I do emphasize when there is a rain \"after a long time\"<\/p>\n","question_id":40179,"tags":["zoology","ethology"],"score":5,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":1300,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3c44cfd152bbd6a9496523b3628503ef?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19799,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19799/user19799","reputation":1,"display_name":"user19799"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a51980d404d08ba2b8c640ce12120c88?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":17617,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/17617/bshane","reputation":1739,"display_name":"bshane"},"score":0,"post_id":40217,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446511810,"comment_id":67530,"body":"Welcome to Biology SE. Very sorry to hear about your cat. Is there a particular reason you are interested in skeletonisation? I have some familiarity with museum techniques for prepar