ently damage the tissue. I doubt this technique is available for routine use in animals, though.     <\/p>\n\n<p>Another interesting technique is <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animal_model_of_ischemic_stroke\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>photothrombosis<\/strong><\/a>. This method is based on the systemic injection of a photosensitive dye named Rose bengal. Subsequent focal illumination of the brain with a cold light source through the intact skull leads to focal cortical infarcts of reproducible size, location and geometry <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0165027002000729\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Schroeter <em>et al<\/em>., 2002)<\/a> . Brain damage is induced due to photo-activation of the dye and subsequent endothelial damage with platelet activation and thrombosis, resulting in local blood flow interruption. The light source can be applied on the intact skull with no need of craniotomy, which allows targeting of any cortical area of interest in a reproducible and non-invasive way <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727176/\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Labat-Gest &amp; Tomasi, 2013)<\/a>. However, although the light source penetrates the skull, I don't think the method is useful for the induction of deep-brain lesions, as I was able to locate only studies using it to model cortical lesions.  <\/p>\n\n<p>Having not answered the question, I'd like to say that either surgical sectioning, or chemical ablation using micro-injection of neurotoxins are the most commonly encountered methods to perform a callosotomy.<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>References<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727176/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Labat-Gest &amp; Tomasi, <em>J Vis Exp<\/em> (2013); <strong>76<\/strong>: 50370<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0165027002000729\" rel=\"nofollow\">Schroeter <em>et al<\/em>., <em>J Neurosci Methods<\/em> (2002); <strong>117<\/strong>(1): 43\u20139<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://thejns.org/doi/pdf/10.3171/ped.2007.106.4.312\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mathew <em>et al<\/em>., <em>J Neurosurgery: Pediatrics<\/em> (2007); <strong>106<\/strong>(4): 312-5<\/a><\/sub><\/p>\n","answer_id":40187,"question_id":40184,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1446461358}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40184/what-are-known-methods-of-non-surgically-disabling-neural-tracts-pathways-esp","last_activity_date":1446478249,"creation_date":1446451241,"answer_count":1,"title":"What are known methods of non-surgically disabling neural tracts/pathways (esp. Corpus Callosum)?","body":"<p>I think I've read something about usage of TTX and optogenetics, but I cannot find the papers for either anymore. Any reference would be much appreciated, especially those concerning mice and the <em>Corpus Callosum<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: By <em>surgical<\/em>, I mean to say <strong>methods<\/strong> that are based on actually <strong>cutting<\/strong> through the tract using a surgical knife (or lasers <em>etcetera<\/em>), as is commonly found in literature.<\/p>\n","question_id":40184,"tags":["neuroscience","methods"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":45,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1446478249},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/FEg3q.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19782,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19782/greg-b","reputation":3,"display_name":"Greg.B"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1446477810,"creation_date":1446477810,"body":"<p>Homeopathic magnesium lotions don't* contain magnesium, so it seems a little irrelevant whether or not magnesium can be absorbed through the skin. However, magnesium ions can <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15080493\" rel=\"nofollow\">definitely be absorbed through the skin<\/a>. There's no reason why that should reduce muscle pain(especially because ions would disperse throughout the bloodstream etc etc), but magnesium can be absorbed through the skin fairly efficiently.<\/p>\n\n<p>*Footnote: they do, but not on purpose. If correctly prepared they would contain zero atoms of magnesium(depending on what 'strength' they are), but that kind of purity is impossible.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40199,"question_id":40193,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40193/absorption-of-topical-magnesium","last_activity_date":1446477810,"creation_date":1446474603,"answer_count":1,"title":"Absorption of Topical Magnesium","body":"<p>Can Magnesium be absorbed through the skin? Some athletes believe that Homeopathic magnesium lotions can reduce muscle pain. I've tried this and it doesn't work nor can I see how it can.<\/p>\n","question_id":40193,"tags":["human-biology"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":40199,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":20,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/93931828e134bd2a141fb66a2373ab8e?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":19652,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19652/j-s","reputation":9,"display_name":"J S"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11ecb2130d870caa97f33b9e9e658e19?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4109,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4109/resonating","reputation":3125,"display_name":"Resonating"},"score":1,"post_id":39997,"edited":false,"creation_date":1445969098,"comment_id":67121,"body":"Are you asking about coconut oil, the consumer product you can buy, or coconut oils, the fats found in coconuts 