o have longer-chain oils and more heavily saturated fats, or even that they definitely do. But it looks like they do, and that would make sense.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40007,"question_id":39997,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1446477357}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39997/is-there-an-evolutionary-advantage-for-coconut-oils-to-be-rich-in-saturated-fats","last_activity_date":1446477357,"creation_date":1445965069,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is there an evolutionary advantage for coconut oils to be rich in saturated fats?","body":"<p>I know that coconut oil is composed of multiple saturated fatty acids, but is there a reason why this would have increased the fitness of the coconut plant?<\/p>\n","question_id":39997,"tags":["evolution","biochemistry","botany","plant-physiology","fat-metabolism"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":96,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1446009654},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cabd5da7746d2afcf7be055d72907e67?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10490,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10490/noncom","reputation":281,"display_name":"noncom","accept_rate":40},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/40197/limits-of-brain-neuronal-spatial-mapping","last_activity_date":1446476365,"creation_date":1446476365,"answer_count":0,"title":"Limits of brain neuronal spatial mapping","body":"<p>It is being claimed that brain maps the world space in (roughly) 1-to-1 correspondance of a place to a neuron (<a href=\"http://knowingneurons.com/2013/04/08/you-are-here-mapping-the-world-with-neurons/\" rel=\"nofollow\">link1<\/a>, <a href=\"http://knowingneurons.com/2014/05/29/navigating-a-3d-world/\" rel=\"nofollow\">link2<\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>My question is: as the mapping happens in 1-to-1 manner, then is it logical to assume that the brain loses the ability to map space anymore when it already has each suitable neuron assigned to a place?<\