ase chain reaction is done on free DNA that has been released from the cell by a variety of chemical or physical methods.<\/p>\n\n<p>There is no cells involved in PCR as the components you don't want are seperated by high-speed centrifugation.<\/p>\n\n<p>PCR also requires the cycling of heat as to aid in the unwinding of DNA for the binding of primers which also allows for the functionality of TAQ polymerase which is a high heat DNA polymerase isolated from the bacterium <em>Thermus aquaticus<\/em>.<\/p>\n\n<p>So unless your talking about a different reaction PCR does not involve any living organisms including cells. They are removed.<\/p>\n","answer_id":40178,"question_id":40175,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0329819d1cfd8d00c4bddc535abe1c94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19770,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19770/b-m","reputation":113,"display_name":"B M"},"score":0,"post_id":40180,"edited":false,"creation_date":1446473830,"comment_id":67495,"body":"Thanks for answering! Can you explain in more detail how the DNA from a microorganism engulfed in the cell membrane of a macrophage will make it through the isolation process? Why does high-speed centrifugation not discard the macrophage entirely? Can denaturation (or another process) as employed in isolation techniques decompose a macrophage&#39;s lipid membrane and the engulfed microorganism&#39;s cell wall?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":40180,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0329819d1cfd8d00c4bddc535abe1c94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19770,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19770/b-m","reputation":113,"display_name":"B M"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446475149,"comment_id":67497,"body":"@BM there are different kits for different types of samples, so if you&#39;re processing samples that have cell walls, make sure you choose the correct reagents. The lysis process is quite harsh, denaturing pretty much everything. Look through some of the information at <a href=\"http://www.qiagen.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">Qiagen<\/a>, one of the most highly-regarded companies in this field. The centrifugation steps are <i>after<\/i> lysis (the other answer is rather confusing in this regard), so you&#39;re not losing any cells."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/476e67c92121154e7910301e56cdfc4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":948,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/948/mattdmo","reputation":7591,"display_name":"MattDMo","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":40180,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0329819d1cfd8d00c4bddc535abe1c94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19770,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19770/b-m","reputation":113,"display_name":"B M"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1446475342,"comment_id":67498,"body":"@BM <a href=\"https://www.qiagen.com/us/resources/download.aspx?id=b3243c93-3ab3-4709-bdf4-2f399b8db5ba&amp;lang=en\" rel=\"nofollow\">Here<\/a> is a selection guide for what type of kit to choose for purifying genomic DNA."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0329819d1cfd8d00c4bddc535abe1c94?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":19770,"link":"http://biology.stacke